prepInstructionText:
In this experiment, you will hear sets of three words and are asked to judge whether the first or last word sounded the most similar to the middle word.

Before you begin the main experiment, we will do a couple of audio checks and practice trials. Please switch off your phone/notifications, ensure that you are in a quiet location without distractions and put on headphones now.

Click the 'Next' button to continue.

First, click 'play' on the audio player to listen to a sample audio clip. Listen as many times as you wish to make sure you have adjusted your device's volume (not the volume on the audio player) to a comfortable listening level with headphones on.



When you're ready to continue, click the 'Next' button.

Next, we will do a short audio test to ensure that your audio listening quality is appropriate for the main task. Please ensure you are wearing headphones.
In each trial, you will hear three tones at a time. You will be asked to decide which tone (first, second, third) was the quietest by clicking a button on the screen (e.g. FIRST sound is QUIETEST).

The task will start immediately when you continue.

When you're ready to begin, click the 'Next' button.
mainInstructionText:
In this experiment, you will listen to words spoken by two people from either Canada or the US. Your task is to judge how similar different pronunciations of the same word sound.

In each trial, you will hear one word repeated three times (e.g. mouse... mouse... mouse). Your task is to listen carefully and decide whether the middle word sounded more like the first word or the last word. If the first word is more similar, press '1' on your keyboard. If the second word is more similar, press '0' on your keyboard.

Please try to respond as quickly as possible without sacrificing accuracy. You will find that some of the pronunciations sound extremely similar. Just go with your instinct and don't overthink your response.

Several breaks are included throughout the experiment â€” during those times, you are welcome to take a few minutes to rest before continuing to the next set of trials.

To begin a few practice trials, press SPACE.
finalInstructionText:
Great, you've finished the practice!

Now we will begin the actual experiment.

When you're ready to begin, press SPACE.
